english:
  title: A Preface Sent to Monk Seonzi Upon His Journey to Mount Geumgang
  author: Choe Hae
  language: eng
  text: |-
    In remote mountains and deep valleys where few human feet ever tread, it is natural that strange things gather. Thus those who follow the teachings of Zhang Daoling call certain peaks the "blessed caves" of immortals, dwelling places of celestial worthies. There, those who disdain the world seek the Way, practicing austerities and refusing grain, vanishing into those peaks never to return. Though I find their detachment from human feeling troubling, I do not greatly dispute with them, for our paths diverge.

    In the eastern reaches where heaven meets the sea stands a mountain the world calls Mount Pungak, yet the monks name it Mount Geumgang. They say this rests upon the Avatamsaka Sutra, which speaks of a bodhisattva dwelling in the eastern sea at a place called Mount Geumgang. I have never read this scripture myself, so I cannot say whether this mountain truly bears that name. Recently someone brought me the Record of Mount Geumgang, written by a monk of Bodae Hermitage, and upon reading it, I found only baseless tales and falsehoods. It claims that fifty-three golden Buddhas sailed across the western seas and arrived at this mountain in the fourth year of Yuan Shi under Emperor Ping of Han, thereby prompting the founding of temples. Yet Buddhist teaching first reached the east in the eighth year of Yongping under Emperor Ming of Han—a full four hundred and one years before those statues allegedly arrived. If we accept this account, then China was shrouded in ignorance, not yet knowing of Buddha, while our eastern land had already erected temples in his honor. The absurdity is beyond measure, and the rest of their claims are equally base.

    And yet, I have heard that in ancient times, many monks of genuine learning entered these mountains, disciplined their practice and refined their conduct, and thus attained enlightenment. Indeed, the mountain lies hundreds of li from human habitation, with sheer cliffs and bottomless chasms everywhere. There are no hermitages to shelter the body, no arable fields for growing sustenance. To dwell there, one must nest in caves or perch in trees like the birds and beasts, sustained only by roots and bark. No one could endure even a single day otherwise. The Buddha's teaching demands that the practitioner be tested through hardship and suffering before understanding is gained. Thus did the master's austerities on Snow Mountain last six years. Indeed, whoever wishes to study this dharma with sincere dedication cannot avoid entering the mountain.

    But alas, these days are different. Hermitages multiply yearly—now nearly a hundred dot the slopes. The great temples—Bodae, Pyohun, Jangan—are built with official support. Soaring halls and magnificent stupas fill the valleys, their gold and jade gleaming so brilliantly they dazzle the eyes. Treasuries hold abundant resources; officials manage the precious stores; vast fields spread across provinces and counties. Even the revenues of Gangneung and Hwanyang are diverted to these mountains. Though famine strikes, no portion is reduced. Each year emissaries ensure that robes, provisions, oil, and salt flow without cease. The monks themselves shirk public duties, while people evade taxation—thousands sit idle, waiting for rice. Yet I have heard of not a single soul who, like those who practiced on Snow Mountain, achieved enlightenment.

    Worse still: they deceive the people, claiming that merely sixty-one glimpses of this mountain guarantee escape from the hells. High and low, from nobles to commoners, families bring wives and children, competing to offer worship. Save when snow blocks the passes or summer floods swell the paths, pilgrims crowd the roads. Among them, widows and unmarried women go and lodge in mountain temples; ugly rumors spread, yet people think nothing strange of it. Officials, fearing the mountain's influence, rush to obey commands. Annual rites send incense down mountain roads. The costs of provision mount into the thousands, and neighboring villagers, exhausted from hosting, cry out in frustration: "Why could this mountain not be elsewhere?"

    Ah, people love this mountain because a bodhisattva dwells there. They revere the bodhisattva because he bestows hidden blessings. Yet these hidden blessings cannot be perceived. So the shaven-headed priests sell the mountain for their own comfort while the people suffer. What more need be said?

    Thus when I see men of letters making pilgrimage, though I lack the strength to stop them, my heart quietly despises it. Now you, Monk Seonzi, journey to this mountain. I write to you what I have long harbored in my breast but never spoken. Since you have already taken the monastic path, why did you delay entering the mountain? Should you meet other pilgrims there, tell them this on my behalf—surely some will recognize the truth in my words.
  footnotes:
    - 'Zhang Daoling (張道陵): Legendary founder of the Way of the Celestial Masters (Daoism), traditionally dated to the 2nd century CE.'
    - '"Blessed caves" (洞天): In Daoist cosmology, sacred mountains with spiritual significance.'
    - 'Emperor Ping of Han (平帝): Reigned 1-6 CE. The date mentioned (甲子, 4 years of Yuan Shi) would be 1 BCE, creating the chronological impossibility Choe Hae points out.'
    - 'Emperor Ming of Han (明帝): Reigned 58-75 CE. The eighth year of Yongping (永平) was 65 CE, traditionally marking Buddhism''s official entry to China.'
    - 'Emperor Wu of Liang (梁武帝): Reigned 502-549 CE. Buddhism became the state religion under his rule.'
    - 'Snow Mountain austerities: Reference to Buddhist tradition of extreme asceticism, particularly associated with practices in mountain monasteries.'
    - 'Sixty-one views (六十一覩): A folk belief (possibly a transcription error in the original) that repeated pilgrimage ensures karmic benefit.'
